- Every difficult conversation contains three simultaneous conversations
    - The apparent subject (the brochure, the money, the schedule) is rarely what makes it difficult
    - Three conversations run in parallel — each with its own errors, its own feelings, its own stakes
    - Managing all three simultaneously is the work; engaging blindly makes each harder
    - The goal: shift from a message delivery stance to a learning conversation
        - Message delivery: I have a conclusion; my job is to make you accept it
        - Learning conversation: I have a story; you have a story; together we have information neither has alone
        - The shift: from debate to exploration, from certainty to curiosity, from "I need you to change" to "I need to understand"
        - Purposes that work: learning their story, expressing your views and feelings, problem-solving together
        - Purposes that backfire: trying to change them, venting or telling them off, hit-and-run

    - The "What Happened?" Conversation
        - Most difficult conversations involve disagreement about what happened, who is right, who meant what, who is to blame
        - Three predictable errors compound the difficulty
        - Error 1: the truth assumption — "I am right, you are wrong"
            - Difficult conversations are almost never about getting the facts right
            - They are about conflicting perceptions, interpretations, and values — what a contract means, which child-rearing book to follow
            - Jack and Michael: they both agree the chart has an error; they disagree about whether it matters and how to handle it
            - Each person makes sense in their own story; both Rory and Aunt Bertha are right from their own perspective
            - Why stories diverge: three systematic sources
                - We have different information
                    - We notice different things: Doug sees floats; Andrew at the same parade sees trucks
                    - What we attend to depends on who we are and what we care about
                    - Randy and Daniel at the same company, living different workplaces based on what each has noticed and experienced
                    - We each have access to different information about ourselves: Jack knows he worked through the night and canceled dinner; Michael doesn't; Michael knows his client blew up over a photograph that morning; Jack doesn't
                - We have different interpretations
                    - Past experiences give meaning to the present: Caroline's Depression-era childhood makes any restaurant meal feel extravagant; Bonnie sees cheapness
                    - We apply different implicit rules: Thelma's rule ("lateness is unprofessional") collides with Ollie's rule ("obsessing about small things is unprofessional")
                    - Rules feel like truths; they are not
                    - Jack's rule: "you should always show appreciation no matter what"; Michael's rule may be: "good friends can be angry with each other without it being personal"
                - Our conclusions reflect self-interest
                    - Howard Raiffa's study: sellers valued a company at 30% above market; buyers valued it at 30% below; each sincerely believing they were being objective
                    - "I sometimes failed to persuade the court that I was right, but I never failed to persuade myself." — Roger Fisher
            - The remedy: shift from certainty to curiosity
                - Instead of "how can they think that?!" ask "I wonder what information they have that I don't?"
                - Instead of "how can they be so irrational?" ask "how might they see the world such that their view makes sense?"
                - Certainty locks you out of their story; curiosity lets you in
                - Also get curious about your own story: what implicit rules are you applying? What past experience is shaping your interpretation?
                - Keiko catches herself: "What does Tony know that I don't? How is he seeing this such that his decision makes sense?"
                    - Tony's story: three hours with football is the one time during the week when he can truly relax; his stress level goes down, almost as if he's meditating; this has a significant impact on his ability to take on the week ahead
                    - None of this was available without curiosity
            - The And Stance: embrace both stories simultaneously
                - The false choice: you can only understand their story by abandoning yours, or hold your position by dismissing theirs
                - "Don't choose between the stories; embrace both. That's the And Stance."
                - It is not "pretend both are right" — it is "stop making them choose"
                - The world is complex: you can feel hurt and they can feel just as hurt; they can be doing their best and you can think it's not good enough; you can feel furious with someone and also feel love and appreciation
                - Even when you're right (smoking is bad; your friend is an alcoholic), merely being right doesn't help
                    - What helps is telling them about the impact and genuinely trying to understand their story
                    - "Until you understand his story, and share yours with him, you can't help him find a way to rewrite the next chapter"
                - The And Stance for delivering bad news
                    - "I'm breaking up with you because it's the right thing for me [here's why], and I understand how hurt you are, and that you think we should try again, and I'm not changing my mind, and I understand that you think I should have been more clear about my confusion earlier, and I don't think that makes me a bad person, and I understand that I've done things that hurt you, and I know I might regret this decision, and I'm still making it.... And, and, and."
                    - "And helps you to be curious and clear."
        - Error 2: the intention invention — "I know what you intended"
            - Intentions are invisible; we assume them from the impact on us; we make them up
            - We assume the worst: when a friend shows up late, we don't think "he ran into someone in need"; we think "jerk, he doesn't care about making me miss the beginning"
            - We treat ourselves more charitably: when you forget to book the tickets it's because you're stressed; when a coworker forgets it's because they're irresponsible
            - Getting their intentions wrong is costly
                - We jump from "they had bad intentions" to "they are a bad person"
                - Once we think we have someone figured out, we see all their actions through that lens
                - Accusing someone of bad intentions creates defensiveness; the accused feels falsely accused, which is one of the most aggravating feelings
                - Self-fulfilling prophecy: you think your boss doesn't trust you; you feel demotivated; your work suffers; she gives you even less responsibility
            - Two key mistakes — Lori and Leo
                - Leo said "why don't you lay off the ice cream?"; Lori felt hurt and humiliated
                - Lori's mistake: "You have this need to control me or put me down" — asserting Leo's intentions as fact
                    - She can't know his intentions; this is an assumption from the impact on her
                - Leo's mistake: "I wasn't trying to hurt you; I was just trying to help you stick to your diet. Why does that make you upset?" — assuming good intentions sanitize bad impact
                    - Every accusation about intent contains two messages: "you meant to hurt me" AND "I was hurt"
                    - Leo defends himself against the first message and completely ignores the second
                    - Often "you intended to hurt me" really means "you don't care enough about me" — a very different message
                    - Leo's intentions may also be more complex than purely angelic: he may have been embarrassed by Lori's eating in front of friends
            - The remedy: disentangle impact and intent
                - For the person who was hurt
                    - Three questions to break the automatic leap: (1) what did they actually say or do? (2) what was the impact on me? (3) what assumption am I making about their intent?
                    - Hold the assumption as a hypothesis: "I'm wondering whether you said it on purpose to embarrass me. I don't know that that's what you intended."
                    - Lori's better opening: "When you said 'why don't you lay off the ice cream,' I felt hurt. Then what I wonder is whether you said it on purpose to embarrass or hurt me."
                - For the person being accused
                    - Listen past the accusation for the feelings
                        - Don't pretend they aren't saying the first thing (the intent accusation); you'll want to respond to it
                        - But neither ignore the second thing (they were hurt); start there
                    - Leo's better response: "Wow. It sounds like what I said really hurt." Then later: "I was thinking I was helping you with your diet. But I can see how saying something in front of everyone would be embarrassing. I wonder why I didn't see that? Maybe I was embarrassed myself."
                    - Be open to reflecting on the complexity of your own intentions
                        - Avoid "my intentions were pure" — think honestly about what was actually motivating you
                        - The husband who stayed home from his sister's hospital visit: perhaps he was embarrassed; perhaps he didn't realize how upsetting it was; "I wonder why I didn't see that"
        - Error 3: the blame frame — "Who is at fault?"
            - Blame is about judging and looks backward; contribution is about understanding and looks forward
            - Blame asks: did they cause this? Was their action wrong? How should they be punished?
            - Contribution asks: how did each of us contribute to this? What can we each do differently going forward?
            - Why blame fails
                - When blame is the goal, learning is the casualty: people become less forthcoming, less open, less willing to apologize
                - Blame hinders problem-solving: should we argue about who let the dog out, or look for the dog?
                - Blame can leave a bad system undiscovered: firing the VP at Commodity Corp didn't fix the culture of silence that produced the bad decision in the first place
            - The contribution system is joint and interactive
                - The pitcher and the batter: whether the batter strikes out or homers depends on both
                - "Only in a B movie is it that simple. In real life causation is almost always more complex."
                - Your assistant packed the wrong storyboards: she felt too intimidated to double-check; you had been snapping at her; she withdrew to avoid your anger; you forgot to double-check; she assumed you usually did
            - Finding your fair share: four hard-to-spot contributions
                - Avoiding until now: not raising the issue is a contribution; your ex-husband has been late picking up the kids for two years but you've never mentioned it's a problem
                    - Complaining to a third party instead of the person with whom you're upset: makes you feel better but puts the third party in the middle and lets the person causing the problem continue
                - Being unapproachable: short-tempered, judgmental, hypersensitive, punitive — your style keeps people from bringing things to you, creating a system of avoidance
                - Intersections: Toby and Eng-An's fighting pattern
                    - Toby's family: his mother had alcohol problems; he was the only one willing to speak up; he has a deep sense that raising and addressing problems immediately is crucial
                    - Eng-An's family: her brother is mentally handicapped; she needed space from constant emotional intensity; she learned not to react too quickly
                    - Toby talks, Eng-An withdraws; Eng-An withdrawing makes Toby feel abandoned; Toby talking makes Eng-An feel smothered; the intersection is the contribution
                    - "Treating an intersection as a question of right versus wrong leads to the death of a great many relationships"
                - Problematic role assumptions: George's family's repetitive dynamic
                    - Seven-year-old George does something annoying; mother asks father to intervene; father yells; mother soothes; George finds another irritating way to get attention
                    - All three are playing their parts; the dynamic serves a function (connecting emotionally) even as it has limitations
            - Two tools for spotting your own contribution
                - Role reversal: "What would they say I'm contributing?" Answer in the first person as them
                - Observer perspective: as a neutral consultant, how would you describe what each person is contributing?
            - Take responsibility for your contribution early
                - Sydney to Miguel: "I apologize for not bringing this up earlier, before it became such a big deal for me. Also, I realize that arranging for us to work together at the beginning of the project may have sent a confusing signal, though all I intended was to improve our professional relationship. What was your reaction?"
                - Taking responsibility first prevents the other person from using your contribution as a deflection
            - Help them understand their contribution
                - Make your observations explicit: describe what they said or did that triggered your reaction
                - Clarify what you would have them do differently, linked to how that would help you change yours
                - "Making a specific request for how the other person can change their contribution in the service of helping you change yours can be a powerful way of helping them understand what they are doing to create and perpetuate the problem"
            - Absorbers and shifters
                - "Shifters" see only others' contributions and none of their own
                - "Absorbers" see only their own contribution and take on all responsibility — they also let others off the hook; responsibility is hoarded and the best solutions less likely to emerge

    - The Feelings Conversation
        - Difficult conversations are not just about what happened; they are at their core about feelings
        - "Engaging in a difficult conversation without talking about feelings is like staging an opera without the music. You'll get the plot but miss the point."
        - Jack still feels hurt and resentful toward Michael months later — even though he never explicitly said "I feel mistreated or underappreciated"
        - Why we suppress feelings
            - Getting too deep into feelings is messy, clouds judgment, seems inappropriate at work
            - Bringing up feelings makes us vulnerable: what if the other person dismisses them, or responds without real understanding?
            - Once we've shared, it's their turn — are we up to hearing their anger and pain?
        - Three ways unexpressed feelings damage conversations
            - They leak: your affect, tone, body language, long pauses, odd detachment, sarcasm, aggressiveness, impatience — studies show most of us can detect when someone is withholding an emotion
            - They burst: Edward tried to control his feelings by containing them; he exploded anyway; the explosion was caused by too little expression, not too much; like a carbonated drink shaken and finally opened, the results are messy
            - They block listening: buried emotions draw the spotlight back to you; you can't genuinely focus on the other person while replaying your own unspoken feelings
        - Finding your feelings
            - Your emotional footprint: the characteristic pattern of which emotions you believe are okay to have and express
                - You may believe longing and sadness are okay but anger is not; anger may be easy for me while shame is off-limits
                - Some of us find it easy to express disappointment but difficult to express affection, pride, or gratitude
            - Accept that all feelings are normal and natural: feelings themselves just are; like arms and legs, they're not inherently good or bad — it's what you do with them that matters
            - Recognize that good people can have bad feelings: everyone feels anger, everyone fails, everyone needs other people
            - Find the bundle of feelings, not just the dominant one
                - Brad thinks he only feels anger at his mother; after making a list he discovers: hopelessness, fear, confusion about his direction, appreciation for her caring, pride in holding out for the right job, shame
                - "In many situations, we are blinded to the complexity of our feelings by one strong feeling that trumps all the others"
            - Find feelings hiding under attributions, judgments, and accusations
                - Emily told Roz she was "self-absorbed and thoughtless" — a judgment, not a feeling; Roz got defensive and attacked back
                - Emily tried again with pure feelings: "I feel hurt. I feel confused about the friendship. I feel embarrassed." Roz was contrite and couldn't stop thanking her.
                - Common translations: feelings become judgments ("if you were a good friend..."), attributions ("why were you trying to hurt me?"), characterizations ("you're inconsiderate"), problem-solving proposals ("you should call me more often")
                - None of these are feelings
            - Don't treat feelings as gospel: negotiate with them
                - Feelings are based on perceptions, and perceptions are negotiable
                - The reef shark: terror evaporates the moment your training lets you identify it as a shark that doesn't prey on people your size; the feeling followed the story
                - Examine your story, your intent assumptions, your contribution — your feelings will begin to shift
                - Jamila's anger at her husband was blocking her ability to express love; once she acknowledged and partially expressed the anger, the love became accessible
        - Expressing feelings without evaluating
            - Rule 2 (stated first): try to get everything you are feeling into the conversation
            - Rule 1: before saying what you are feeling, negotiate with your feelings
            - Frame feelings back into the problem: if feelings are the issue, they are the business at hand; your feelings need not be rational to be expressed
            - Express the full spectrum, not just the dominant emotion
                - Brad to his mother: "When you ask me how the job search is going, I feel a couple of things. One thing I feel is angry because I've asked you not to bring it up. But at the same time, part of me is appreciative, and reassured that things will be okay."
                - "When I think about the search, I end up feeling ashamed, like maybe I'm wasting my potential or letting you down."
            - Express without judging, attributing, or blaming
                - "I feel frustrated. You didn't send the letter out." — feeling plus fact, no blame
                - "It's your fault that I felt hurt" — mixes a feeling with a causal attribution; fighting about causation rather than engaging with the feeling
                - "You are so damn undependable!" — a judgment, no feeling at all
                - "I feel..." is the formulation
            - Don't monopolize: both sides probably have strong feelings; get both into the conversation before moving to solutions
        - Acknowledging feelings before problem-solving
            - Acknowledgment means letting the other person know their feelings made an impression on you, that they matter, that you are working to understand them
            - "Wow, I never knew you felt that way." "It sounds like this is really important to you." "Before I give you a sense of what's going on with me, tell me more about your feeling that I talk down to you."
            - It's tempting to jump over feelings to "fix" them: "Well, let's see. If you're feeling lonely, I guess I'll try to spend more time with you." — this is too soon; it short-circuits before the person feels heard
            - Acknowledgment is not agreement: the supervisor who acknowledges the subordinate feeling hurt and betrayed by a transfer, while still maintaining the transfer is right
            - Max and Julie's wedding: once Max shared his feelings of sadness and pride with his daughter, the logistical disagreements resolved almost immediately
            - The community meeting on racial tensions: "I don't want to change their minds. I just wanted to share my story, to share my feelings. Because now I know: they care enough about me to just listen."

    - The Identity Conversation
        - Difficult conversations are difficult partly because they put our self-image at risk
        - Before, during, and after: "the Identity Conversation is about what I am saying to myself about me"
        - Three core identity questions: Am I competent? Am I a good person? Am I worthy of love?
        - Ben is terrified to tell his boss he is leaving — not because of any practical consequence, but because his sense of himself as a loyal soldier is at stake
        - Even delivering bad news triggers identity: "I'm the person people respect for finding a way to do it, not for shutting the door"
        - An identity quake can knock you off balance
            - Images of yourself are hardwired to your adrenal response; shaking them up causes an unmanageable rush of anxiety or anger
            - Well-being is replaced with depression, hope with hopelessness, efficacy with fear — all while you're trying to engage in the extremely delicate task of communicating clearly
        - The vulnerability: all-or-nothing thinking
            - "I'm either competent or incompetent, good or evil, worthy of love or not"
            - This binary leaves our identity extremely unstable, making us hypersensitive to any information that might contradict our positive self-image
            - Two failure modes when negative information arrives
                - Denial: "My boss knows business but not chemistry. He doesn't appreciate my contributions." — working hard to keep the feedback out
                - Exaggeration: one small mistake → "I'm a catastrophic failure" → "I'm worthless" → "No one will ever love me"
            - All-or-nothing identities are as sturdy as a two-legged stool
        - Building a grounded identity
            - Grounded doesn't mean perfect; it means complex and stable enough to hear hard things
            - Step 1: become aware of which identity question is at stake for you in this conversation
                - Which of the three core questions is this conversation threatening?
                - Jimmy's discovery: his deepest fear in changing how he relates to his family was that they would reject the new version of him
            - Step 2: accept three things about yourself
                - You will make mistakes: accepting this takes the pressure off; any given mistake can still be upsetting without being evidence that you are fundamentally incompetent or bad; Rita violated Isaiah's confidence and could only begin to repair the relationship once she could admit she made a mistake
                - Your intentions are complex: Sally's relationship with Evan wasn't purely selfless — there was loneliness and self-protection in her behavior too; accepting this lets her respond genuinely: "Some of what you're saying makes sense. I was lonely, and being with you helped."
                - You have contributed to the problem: Walker's fear of hearing from his daughter that he wasn't a good father keeps him from having a genuine conversation with her; if he can accept his contribution — away a lot, not always supportive, promises not kept — he can approach her with compassion instead of fear; "I wish I'd been there for you more often. I'm so sorry and sad that I wasn't"
        - During the conversation: regain your balance when you lose it
            - "We don't want to quake-proof your sense of self. Grappling with identity issues is what life and growth are all about."
            - Four stabilizing moves
                - Let go of trying to control their reaction
                    - Holding "they must not get upset" as a goal means you lose your balance whenever they do
                    - When telling your kids about the divorce: their being upset is their right; "don't measure the success of the conversation by whether or not they get upset"
                    - The And Stance: let them react however they need to, and give them space for it, while staying grounded in your own position and purposes
                - Prepare for their response
                    - Think through in advance the most difficult responses you might receive
                    - Having already "met" those scenarios in imagination reduces their power to destabilize you
                - Imagine the future to gain perspective
                    - In one year, in ten years, in forty years — how significant will today's events look?
                    - "Today feels big right now, but from the perspective of many days hence, it will look pretty small"
                - Take a break if needed
                    - When you are flooded — anxiety so high you cannot think clearly — the most skilled move is often to pause explicitly
                    - "I'm feeling overwhelmed by what you just said. I want to take it seriously, but I can't right now. Can we come back to this in an hour?"
                    - This is self-knowledge in service of the conversation, not avoidance

- Preparing for a difficult conversation
    - Before you can have a good conversation, you have to prepare — not a script, but a clearing of the ground
    - The preparation checklist (used by Jack in Chapter 12)
        - Sort out the Three Conversations: each party's story? information? feelings? identity stakes?
        - Understand your emotions: your emotional footprint; the bundle of emotions you're carrying
        - Ground your identity: which question is at stake? What do you need to accept?
    - Deciding whether to raise it
        - There is no "right choice" — there is only thinking clearly and making a considered choice
        - Work through the Three Conversations before deciding
        - Three kinds of conversations that don't make sense
            - The real conflict is inside you
                - Carmen's scheduling resentment: once she understood that managing the schedule was her way of staying connected to her children (identity issue), the conversation she thought she needed became unnecessary
            - There's a better way to address the issue than talking
                - Walter's mother kept asking when he was coming home; the contribution system revealed he was contributing by pulling away; the change needed was in his own behavior, not in a conversation about the topic
                - He began phoning more often, sending short notes, inviting her to visit just for fun; slowly the questions about his return decreased
                - Fran and the toll collector: she wrote the Turnpike Authority a letter instead of confronting the collector directly
            - Your purposes are off-base
                - You can't change other people: paradoxically, trying to change someone rarely results in change; engaging in mutual learning often does result in change
                - Don't focus on short-term relief at long-term cost: Janet told Sylvie off and felt good for fifteen minutes; then she realized she'd made the situation worse by feeding the antagonism
                - Don't hit-and-run: "Late again, eh?" leaves the person defensive and frustrated without the exchange needed for anything to actually change; if you're going to talk, really talk; it takes at least ten minutes
        - Three purposes that make conversations worth having
            - Learning their story: their information, interpretations, feelings, identity issues
            - Expressing your views and feelings: what's important for you to say about your story, intentions, contributions, feelings, identity issues
            - Problem-solving together: given what each of you has learned, what would improve the situation going forward?
        - "These three purposes accommodate the fact that you and the other person see the world differently, that you each have powerful feelings, and that you each have your own identity issues to work through."
        - Letting go when you decide not to raise it
            - Sometimes you decide not to engage; holding on inside the relationship becomes too painful or exhausting
            - Other times it's not that easy: you've decided to move on but the story still carries emotional punch
            - Four liberating assumptions
                - It's not my responsibility to make things better; it's my responsibility to do my best: Karenna accepting that sometimes there are limits — you cannot always make a relationship more nourishing or more durable
                - They have limitations too: no matter how clearly you share how much their drinking hurts you, they may not have the capacity to be different right now; Alison after a lifetime of being bossy couldn't change overnight
                - This conflict is not who I am: Rob's professional identity consumed by being the opposition faction; when his side gained control, he didn't know how to see himself
                - Letting go doesn't mean I no longer care: David, whose brother was murdered: "I've begun to see the power in forgiving each of them — my brother and the man who murdered him. Letting go of my rage doesn't mean I let go of my love for my brother. I still talk to him. But the conversations aren't so hard. I can miss him terribly without the clutter of so many other feelings."
            - "You're allowed to give up." You cannot change other people; when you finally give up the idea that you have the power to change others, you are giving up something you never had anyway

- Having the learning conversation
    - Beginning: the Third Story
        - The problem with beginning inside your story
            - "If you contest Dad's will, it's going to tear the family apart" — inside Jason's story; triggers Jill's defensiveness immediately
            - "We need to talk about your problem with getting the dishes done" — tact or not, still Jason's story
            - "I was very upset by what you said in front of our supervisor" — inside your story; positions the other person as the problem before any content has been shared
        - The Third Story: a description both parties can sign on to
            - The story a keen neutral observer would tell — someone with no stake in your particular problem
            - Urban planner, marriage counselor, mutual friend: each can identify the gap between the two sides' stories
            - Mediators don't have magical intuition; they rely on a formula: describe the gap between the parties in a way that rings true for both sides simultaneously
            - "Jason and Jill have different preferences around when dishes are done and different standards for cleanliness. Each is unhappy with the other's approach."
            - Jason's Third Story opening: "Jill, you and I seem to have different preferences about when the dishes get done. I wonder if that's something we could talk about?"
        - How to formulate the Third Story
            - Remove the judgment from the description
            - Describe the problem as a difference: "different preferences," "different understandings," "different views on this"
            - You don't need to know what their story is to include it — just acknowledge it's there
            - "My sense is that you and I see this situation differently. I'd like to share how I'm seeing it and learn more about how you're seeing it."
        - Extending the invitation
            - Describe your purposes (learning their perspective, sharing yours, figuring out how to go forward) so they know what they're agreeing to
            - Invite, don't impose: the task of describing the problem is itself a joint task; be open to their modifications
            - Make them your partner in figuring it out: don't cast them as "the problem" or in an unappealing role
                - "Can you help me understand...?" — advisor role
                - "Let's work on how we might..." — partnership
                - "I wonder whether it's possible to..." — positions them as potential hero
                - "The story I'm telling in my head is that you're being inconsiderate. I know at some level that's unfair to you. I need you to help me put things in better perspective."
        - If they start the conversation: you can still step to the Third Story
            - Take whatever they say and use it as their half of the description
            - Jill: "We need to talk about how you ruin all our meals by being so obsessive"
            - Jason: "It sounds like you're pretty unhappy with how I handle the dishes. I have trouble with how you deal with them too, so I think we each have different preferences and assumptions around that. That seems like a good thing for us to talk about."
        - Be persistent
            - Ruth opening with Brian about Lexi: "It seems to me that we're having a hard time being clear with each other about how likely it is that you'll make it for your time with Lexi."
            - Brian expected blame for the specific recent incident; it took several exchanges before he understood what kind of conversation Ruth was proposing
            - Brian eventually: "Sure. I don't want to upset Lexi."
        - Special cases
            - Delivering bad news: put the bad news up front; don't trick them into saying it; don't bury it in two hours of "issues"
                - "We've talked a lot about how important it is to you for us to come for Christmas, and also how difficult it is financially and emotionally for us to do that. I'm calling because Juan and I have decided we are going to spend this Christmas here. It was a really difficult decision."
            - Making requests: replace "I deserve a raise" with "I'd like to explore whether a raise might make sense. Here's my reasoning. How do you see it?"
                - Your boss has information you don't have; you genuinely don't know if you deserve it until you've explored it with them
            - Revisiting conversations that have gone badly: talk about how to talk before trying again
                - "I know that in the past when I've raised the question of racism in the department, people have sometimes felt accused. I don't mean to accuse anyone. I'd like to talk about how we each react to that conversation and whether there's a better way to address these issues."
                - Your friend who gets defensive about her overbooked schedule: "I definitely get the sense that you don't like discussing your schedule. The problem for me is that I feel worried. I don't seem to know how to share that in a way that's helpful. I was wondering if you had any advice."
    - Listening: from the inside out
        - Authentic listening begins with an internal stance of genuine curiosity
            - The decisive shift: from "I understand" to "Help me understand"
            - Everything else — the questions, paraphrasing, acknowledgment — follows from genuine curiosity
            - Greta's first conversation with her mother (the diabetes and exercise regime): assertion, explanation, problem-solving — mother shuts down
            - Greta's second conversation: questions, paraphrasing, acknowledgment — discovers her mother's fear (grandmother died of the condition), her grief, her loneliness, the actual practical obstacle (she doesn't understand the regimen)
        - Your internal voice is the biggest obstacle to listening
            - Like a personal assistant whose job is to make sure no one bothers you; when triggered, becomes an armed bodyguard
            - "I'm so furious!" / "I can't believe she thinks that about me!" / "When it's my turn I'm going to make four points" — while the other person is still talking
            - Don't suppress it; turn it up; pay attention to it; only then can you begin to manage it
            - Then negotiate it toward curiosity: "What might be right about what they're saying? What don't I know about their perspective?"
            - Managing your internal voice
                - When it's running loudly, you may need to express it first before trying to listen
                - "I want to listen and I care about what you have to say, but I can't listen right now. Often it's enough to give a headline: 'I'm surprised to hear you say that. I think I disagree, but say more about how you see it.'"
        - Three listening skills
            - Inquiry: ask only to learn
                - The only good reason to ask a question is to learn; you can tell whether a question will help or hurt by thinking about why you asked it
                - Don't make statements disguised as questions: "Are we there yet?" — really means "I feel restless"; "Is golf so important that you need to play it this often?" — not a question, an assertion
                - Don't cross-examine: "But isn't it true that...?" "If so, how do you explain...?" — these are assertions with question marks
                - Ask concrete questions: "Say more about how you see things." "What information might you have that I don't?" "What impact have my actions had on you?" "Can you say more about why you think this is my fault?"
                - Ross after coaching: "Say more about how you judge dedication, and what you've observed in me that suggests I'm not as dedicated as you'd like." — discovers his boss equates dedication with social attendance, not just working late
            - Paraphrasing: restate in your own words
                - Two purposes: verify you understood; let them know you understood
                - "So keeping to the regimen would feel like accepting something that you don't really totally accept yet?" — Greta's paraphrase; mother confirms and opens further
                - Paraphrasing also helps them listen to you: "When the other person is not listening, the reason is usually that they don't feel heard. If the block to their listening is that they don't feel heard, then the way to remove the block is by helping them feel heard."
            - Acknowledgment: let them know what they said made an impression
                - Not agreement; letting them know their feelings matter and you are working to understand
                - "Sounds like you feel really hurt and betrayed. I can see why that would be upsetting."
                - Supervisor: "I acknowledge your feelings without agreeing with your conclusion. You feel hurt and betrayed, and I also think this transfer is the right decision and overall not unfair. We should talk about why."
                - Acknowledgment is a journey, not a destination: we are each too complex to be fully understood; people care more that you are trying than that you have succeeded
    - Expressing: speak for yourself with clarity and power
        - Your primary task is not to persuade, impress, trick, outwit, or convert; it is to express what you see and why, how you feel, and who you are
        - You're entitled (yes, you)
            - "We are all equal in the eyes of God" — the professor's advice to John before meeting the intimidating judge
            - "My views and feelings are as legitimate, valuable, and important as yours — no more, but no less"
            - Failure to express keeps you out of the relationship: Angela broke off her engagement because her fiancé was "too nice" — he never stated a preference, never argued, never raised his voice; she felt something was missing: him
            - Callie took the risk of sharing her stories about being called names as a child; her colleagues felt encouraged to share their own stories; she offered them the opportunity, perhaps for the first time, to understand and care about her
            - Beware self-sabotage: you go through the motions of trying, incompetently, so that in the end you fail; you wait to speak until there's not enough time; all your points disappear from your head
        - Start with what matters most
            - Charlie gave Gage advice about debate and drinking; what he was actually feeling: admiration for his younger brother, guilt about how he'd treated Gage when young, deep need to feel like a good brother who was loved in return
            - "I needed him. I needed Gage's help in being a good brother." — Gage was riveted; the whole nature of the conversation changed
            - "Have I said what is at the heart of the matter for me? Have I shared what is at stake?"
        - Don't rely on subtext; say it directly
            - "Is golf so important that you need to play it this often?" — a statement disguised as a question; signals anger but leaves the cause completely obscure
            - "Honey, you are simply playing too much golf!" — opinion presented as fact; raises questions it doesn't answer
            - Better: "I'd like to spend more time with you, and Saturday mornings were one of the few times we had that. As a result, I'm finding your interest in golf irritating."
            - Easing in (Professor Argyris): leading through hints and indirect questions; conveys three messages: "I have a view," "this is too embarrassing to discuss directly," "I'm not going to be straight with you"
        - The Me-Me And for complex feelings
            - "I do think you are bright and talented, and I think you're not working hard enough."
            - "I feel relieved and happy that I finally went through with the divorce — it was the right decision. And I do miss him sometimes."
            - Useful for overcoming fear of being misunderstood: "I have a view on this that I want to share, and I have to say that I'm nervous about doing so because I'm afraid it may sound self-serving."
        - Three clarity guidelines
            - Don't present your conclusions as the truth
                - "Spanking children is just plain wrong" → "I believe spanking children is wrong" or "I feel sad and frightened when I hear of a child being spanked"
                - Watch for "inappropriate," "should," "professional" — judgments that look like facts
                - This doesn't say there is no truth; it distinguishes opinion from fact and enables a real conversation rather than a defensiveness fight
            - Share where your conclusions come from
                - You can't understand my reluctance about private school unless you know about the fear I felt the first few months, the sense of never quite fitting in, the guilt that my parents couldn't buy a car because they were paying my tuition
                - "Tell that story with all the vividness and detail that's in your head"
            - Don't exaggerate with "always" and "never"
                - Invites an argument about frequency; suggests change is impossible
                - "When you tell me my suit reminds you of wrinkled curtains, I feel hurt. Criticizing my clothes feels like an attack on my judgment and makes me feel incompetent. I wish I could feel more often like you believed in me."
        - Help them understand you
            - Use analogies: "It's like your fear of flying — when I try to tell you to relax during takeoff it has no impact; this is the same sort of thing for me"
            - Ask them to paraphrase back: "Would you mind just playing back what you've heard me say so far?"
            - Ask how they see it differently: not "do you agree?" (invites polite evasion) but "how do you see this differently?" (surfaces real reactions)
    - Problem-solving: taking the lead
        - You may be trying to have a learning conversation while they're still arguing about who's right
        - Reframing: translate their unhelpful statements into Three Conversations concepts
            - Take the essence of what they say and translate it into a more helpful framing
            - "I'm right, and there are no two ways about it!" → "I want to make sure I understand your perspective. You obviously feel strongly. I'd also like to share my perspective."
            - "You hurt me on purpose!" → "I can see that you're feeling really angry about what I did. It wasn't my intention. Can you say more about how you felt?"
            - "This is all your fault!" → "I'm sure I've contributed to the problem; I think we both have. Rather than focus on whose fault this is, I'd like to look at how we each contributed."
            - "You are the nastiest person I've ever met." → "It sounds like you're feeling really badly."
            - Sydney reframing Miguel persistently: each time he returns to blame or cultural attribution, she translates back to the contribution frame; eventually: "I suppose I could have also asked you if things were okay, or if I had offended you for some reason. And maybe we should have just talked about our expectations of each other up front."
            - "You can reframe anything the other person says to move toward a learning conversation"
        - Naming the dynamic: when reframing isn't enough
            - Step outside the conversation's content; address the pattern of how the conversation is going
            - "I've tried to say what I was thinking three times now, and each time you've started talking over me. I don't know whether you're aware that it's happening, but I'm finding it frustrating."
            - "Here's what I'm noticing. I ask you if you are feeling hurt, and you say 'No, no, of course not.' But you keep acting toward me in ways that people act when they're hurt or mad. It seems the best thing to do is to figure out what I'm doing that might be upsetting you."
            - "Hang on a second. Several times now, when I've said things important to me, you've gotten very angry to the point where I feel threatened. If you're trying to intimidate me, it won't work. I really do want to know what's upsetting you, and I want us to find a way to talk about it that doesn't feel intimidating to me."
            - "Okay, we're deadlocked. Your solution is that I should give in. As a process, that doesn't feel fair to me. What's a fair and efficient way to decide when we don't agree?"
            - These moves "sound slightly awkward — not how regular people talk"; that's part of the point — the awkwardness signals you are stepping outside the flow to examine the process
        - Problem-solving when understanding has been reached
            - Sometimes simply sorting out the Three Conversations clears the issues; but not always
            - Create possibilities: Alita can't run on time without a structural overhaul; but a sign in the waiting room explaining why appointments run late actually meets some of the patients' real concerns — they want to understand, and they want to feel acknowledged that she cares
            - Dig for underlying interests
                - Positions are what people say they want; interests are the underlying needs, desires, fears, and concerns
                - "Be on time" (position); underlying interest: "we want families to feel comfortable with Earl more quickly"
                - Earl's solution: asked his supervisor to describe him as a semiprofessional bluegrass banjo player; families came intrigued rather than surprised; his appearance attested to his courage to be himself — a lesson he was effectively teaching them and their children
                - Three buckets for interests behind feedback
                    - Helping you: they see ways you could improve or dangers you don't see
                    - Helping themselves and the relationship: "you travel too much" may mean "I feel neglected"
                    - Helping the organization or someone else: your boss can't give you a higher rating because it wouldn't be fair to others
            - Generate options
                - "The number one reason we don't come up with good options is that we simply don't think to try. So, try."
                - Some options solve the whole problem; others are process options: "We'll try it your way and then take stock" or "I'll draw the chicken more realistically and we can show both to the committee"
                - You don't need a final determination about who is right; agree on a process that feels fair to both
            - If you still can't agree: consider your alternatives
                - Henry: he can stay or go, but if he goes he needs to explain why and accept the consequences; he may return Monday to find Rosario is more respecting of him for holding his ground
                - "Most difficult conversations are not, in actuality, a single conversation. They are a series of exchanges and explorations that happen over time."
